{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520334"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:23:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:23:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13184"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13184"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.12,0.1,0.13,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101534"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5620"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83973"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"253"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9582"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10174"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13437"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44909"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101534"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman undergoes a mitral valve replacement operation. While the operation was long, it was uneventful with no major complications. One day later, the patient reports that she still has significant chest pain at the incisional site. Later that day she develops dyspnoea and tachycardia but is normotensive. She also reports a cough producing frothy and clear sputum. Her medical history includes coronary artery disease and mitral regurgitation. She has smoked ten cigarettes a day for 32 years and drinks alcohol socially. On examination, chest movements are diminished on the right side with basal dullness and decreased air entry.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following post-operative measures might have reduced the risk of this complication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deep breathing exercises","Prophylactic ceftriaxone and amoxicillin","Strict fluid restriction","Prophylactic heparin","Nil by mouth post operatively"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation involving chest pain, tachycardia and a cough with clear sputum as well as the examination findings are most consistent with atelactasis (without infection). Atelectasis is a significant and common post-operative complication that needs to be avoided as it can lead to more serious complications such as LRTI. The risk of developing atelectasis can be reduced pre-operatively by stopping smoking, intra-operatively by interventions such as local anaesthetic infiltration to the wound and post-operatively with measures such as encouraging the patient to cough, adequate analgesia, early mobilisation and \u003Cstrong\u003Edeep breathing exercises\u003C/strong\u003E under the supervision of a respiratory physiotherapist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotic prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E may have a role for prevention of wound site infection and pneumonia among other infections and should be discussed on a case to case basis. This patient does not have any signs of an obvious infection. In addition, this patient is only day two post-operative, which is often too early for an operation-related infection to be easily identified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrict fluid restriction\u003C/strong\u003E is often used in part of the management of fluid overloaded patients (e.g. acute heart failure patients). This patient does not have signs of cardiogenic pulmonary oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic heparin\u003C/strong\u003E is used to prevent deep venous thrombosis and pulmonary embolus (PE). A patient with PE typically presents with pleuritic chest pain and dyspnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKeeping the patient \u003Cstrong\u003Enil by mouth post-operatively\u003C/strong\u003E has little role in preventing atelectasis. While it may prevent aspiration of food contents, this patient is not at high risk of aspiration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atelactasis is a common complication of surgery (especially trans-thoracic procedures)","The most effective treatments for post-operative atelectasis are deep breathing exercises and chest physiotherapy."],"references":["Ellis H, Calne RY, Watson CJE. Lecture notes. General surgery. Thirteenth edition. Chichester, West Sussex\u202f; Ames, Iowa: John Wiley \u0026 Sons Inc; 2016. Chapter 4 Postoperative Complications p. 16-19","TeachMeSurgery Post-Operative Atelectasis. Available at https://teachmesurgery.com/perioperative/cardiorespiratory/atelectasis/ Last updated: December 26 2021. Accessed September 13 2023.","Wang J, Deng N, Qi F, Li Q, Jin X, Hu H. The effectiveness of postoperative rehabilitation interventions that include breathing exercises to prevent pulmonary atelectasis in lung cancer resection patients: a systematic review and meta-analysis. BMC Pulm Med. 2023 Jul 27;23(1):276. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37501067/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83973"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13184"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83973"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T14:30:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T14:32:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5620"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101534"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/33"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiothoracic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i